  "author_association": "MEMBER",
  "body": "In order for VCP to verify SDK endpoint certificates, the vCenter server certificates must be signed by a known CA.  If a vCenter certificate signer is not trusted, the existing options are to either update the system CA bundle or set `insecure-flag = true` in the `--cloud-config` to disable vCenter certificate verification.\r\n\r\nThe VCP should provide an optional `ca-file` configuration option, which can be used configure `TLSClientConfig.RootCAs` via\r\nhttps://github.com/vmware/govmomi/blob/78f12ebf2ab43043db143254f94cedf79524f468/vim25/soap/client.go#L189-L194\r\n\r\nThe VCP should also provide an optional `thumbprint` configuration, which is per vCenter connection and does not require a CA file:\r\nhttps://github.com/vmware/govmomi/blob/78f12ebf2ab43043db143254f94cedf79524f468/vim25/soap/client.go#L220-L226\r\n\r\nvCenter certificate thumbprints can be obtained using a Web browser, the openssl CLI or the `govc about.cert` command:\r\nhttps://github.com/vmware/govmomi/blob/master/govc/USAGE.md#aboutcert\r\n\r\nThe govmomi simulator provides access to the test server's thumbprint, which can be used in tests, for example:\r\nhttps://github.com/vmware/govmomi/blob/78f12ebf2ab43043db143254f94cedf79524f468/simulator/simulator_test.go#L336-L351\r\n\r\nWithin the VCP tests against vcsim, InsecureFlag is currently set to `true`:\r\nhttps://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/65a819338a640faf6ddee9d6eea4559a20106c56/pkg/cloudprovider/providers/vsphere/vsphere_test.go#L112\r\n\r\nWe should add tests for both the `ca-file` and `thumbprint` options that adjust the configuration to test these options with `InsecureFlag = false`.\r\n\r\n/kind feature\r\n/sig vmware\r\n",
